SIMPLE: stern
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stern
<hw>Stern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>stearn</ets> a
kind of bird. See <er>Starling</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The
black tern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stern
<hw>Stern</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sterner</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sternest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sterne</ets>,
<ets>sturne</ets>, AS. <ets>styrne</ets>; cf. D. <ets>stuurish</ets>
stern, Sw. <ets>stursk</ets> refractory. ⟦root⟧166.]</ety> <def>Having a
certain hardness or severity of nature, manner, or aspect; hard; severe;
rigid; rigorous; austere; fixed; unchanging; unrelenting; hence,
serious; resolute; harsh; <as>as, a <ex>stern</ex>resolve; a
<ex>stern</ex> necessity; a <ex>stern</ex> heart; a <ex>stern</ex> gaze;
a <ex>stern</ex> decree.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>sterne</qex> wind so loud gan to rout.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would outstare the <qex>sternest</qex> eyes that look.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When that the poor have cried, Caesar hath wept;⟦br⟧
Ambition should be made of <qex>sterner</qex> stuff.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stern</qex> as tutors, and as uncles hard.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These barren rocks, your <qex>stern</qex> inheritance.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gloomy; sullen; forbidding; strict; unkind;
hard-hearted; unfeeling; cruel; pitiless.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stern
<hw>Stern</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>stj⟦omac⟧rn</ets> a
steering, or a doubtful AS. <ets>ste⟦oacute⟧rn</ets>. ⟦root⟧166. See
<er>Steer</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The helm or
tiller of a vessel or boat; also, the rudder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The after or rear end of a ship
or other vessel, or of a boat; the part opposite to the stem, or
prow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: The post of management or direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And sit chiefest <qex>stern</qex> of public weal.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The hinder part of anything.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The tail of an animal; -- now used only of the tail
of a dog.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By the stern</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See
<cref>By the head</cref>, under <er>By</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stern
<hw>Stern</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Being in the stern, or being astern;
<as>as, the <ex>stern</ex> davits</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stern board</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a going or
falling astern; a loss of way in making a tack; <as>as, to make a
<ex>stern board</ex></as>. See <er>Board</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8
<sd>(b)</sd>.</cd> -- <col><b>Stern chase</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>See under <er>Chase</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A stern chaser.</cd> -- <col><b>Stern chaser</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a cannon placed in a ship's stern, pointing
backward, and intended to annoy a ship that is in pursuit.</cd> --
<col><b>Stern fast</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a rope used to
confine the stern of a ship or other vessel, as to a wharf or buoy.</cd>
-- <col><b>Stern frame</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the framework
of timber forms the stern of a ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Stern
knee</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Sternson</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Stern
port</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a port, or opening, in the stern
of a ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Stern sheets</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>that part of an open boat which is between the stern and the aftmost
seat of the rowers, -- usually furnished with seats for passengers.</cd>
-- <col><b>Stern wheel</b></col>, <cd>a paddle wheel attached to the
stern of the steamboat which it propels.</cd></cs><-- thus,
<col><b>stern wheeler</b></col>. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sternage</ent>⟦br⟧
